    <div class="well">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-12 text-dark">
                <h1 class="text-center">CONSTITUTION OF IEEE</h1>

                <div class="col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2">
                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>PREAMBLE</em></h4>

                    <p>We, the students of IEEE, organize this Purdue University-West Lafayette Student Branch of IEEE to assist our members in their technical pursuits, to support the projects of our committees, and to build social relationships between our members and others on this campus and in the technical community.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE I</em><br>Name</h4>

                    <p>The name of this organization is IEEE. The pronunciation is “Eye-triple-E”. When necessary to differentiate this student organization from the international professional association of the same name, the name of Purdue IEEE Student Organization is used.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE II</em><br>Purpose</h4>

                    <p>The purposes of this organization are:</p>

                    <p>SECTION 1. To serve as a Student Branch of IEEE at the Purdue University-West Lafayette campus and operate in accordance with the Constitution and Bylaws of the IEEE.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. To disseminate knowledge of the theory and practice of all aspects of electrical engineering, electronics, radio, allied branches of engineering or the related arts and sciences, as well as the furtherance of the professional development of the students.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 3. To promote and foster activities for the education of the members in various topics in electrical and computer engineering, computer science, and other technical fields such as robotics, automation, electromechanics, optics, networking, software, and the like.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 4. To enhance the professional development of its members through events and programming useful to the growth of students.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 5. To encourage networking and professional relationships among our members, other student organizations, our partners in industry, and the global technical community through IEEE.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 6. To advocate for the strength of an education from Purdue University and to encourage younger students to pursue careers in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM).</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE III</em><br>Definition of Membership</h4>

                    <p>SECTION 1. Membership and participation are free from discrimination on the basis of race, religion, color, sex, age, national origin or ancestry, genetic information, marital status, parental status, sexual orientation, gender identity and expression, disability, or status as a veteran.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. The membership shall consist of (1) Student and Graduate Student members of IEEE at Purdue University, (2) the Branch Counselor, the Primary Advisor, and secondary advisors (faculty or staff) at Purdue University, and (3) honorary members recognized by the Executive Committee.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 3. In compliance with IEEE Student Branch guidelines, the IEEE shall select a Branch Counselor from the faculty of Purdue University who holds active membership in IEEE. This individual may also be selected as the Primary Advisor or as a secondary advisor of the student organization as mandated by Purdue University.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 4. Current undergraduate and graduate student members are entitled to full rights and voting privileges as members of the Student Branch while faculty or staff at Purdue University are entitled to the same rights except to hold office or vote.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 5. All current undergraduate and graduate student members may join the Purdue IEEE Student Organization. Reporting requirements of IEEE may restrict membership definitions to include students actively holding Student or Graduate Student levels of membership within the international organization.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 6.  Active membership shall be defined as attending three or more general assemblies, social functions, officer meetings, or committee meetings in an academic year.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 7. Any member displaying unprofessional, inappropriate, or dangerous behavior or engaging in illegal activities while representing IEEE or Purdue University may be subject to disciplinary actions. Such actions may include (1) an email describing the incident and a demand to cease such behavior or activities, (2) review before the officers and committee chairs, (3) enactment of a probationary period where membership rights may be suspended upon a vote of two-thirds of the officers and committee chairs present and voting, and (4) formal disassociation and expulsion from the Purdue IEEE Student Organization upon a vote of two-thirds of the officers and committee chairs present and voting. Outside of the actions outlined above, any incident may be reported to the Office of Student Rights and Responsibilities or the Office of Professional Practice.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE IV</em><br>Elections</h4>

                    <p>SECTION 1. The elected officers of IEEE shall include a President, a Vice President, a Treasurer, a Secretary, an Industrial Relations Head, and an Event Coordinator.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. To be eligible for office, an officer must be a student at Purdue University, be in good standing with the Purdue IEEE Student Organization, and not hold another elected office. Officers are encouraged to enroll as IEEE members if not at the time of election.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 3. The term of office shall be for one year, starting on June 1. Elections should occur before May 1.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 4. The members present at elections shall give nominees for each office. For a nominee to become a candidate for an office, another member must second the nomination and the nominee must accept. Candidates will be removed from the ballot for a subsequent office prior to voting if they are elected to another office earlier during elections.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 5. The members shall select the elected officers by a two-round voting process. For each office, the voting members may cast a single vote for one of the candidates. The candidate with a majority of votes wins. Should no candidate receive a majority of votes, a second round of voting will begin with only the top two candidates on the ballot. The order of voting is that mentioned in Article IV, Section 1. Non-officer elected positions shall be decided after the elections for the officers.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 6. In the event the members at elections yield a tie for the top candidates for an office, the current elected officers and committee chairs shall decide that election by the method described in Article IV, Section 5. Should the current elected officers and committee chairs produce a further tie, then the winning candidate will be decided by sortition.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 7. Presence for a vote shall be defined by the ability to hear and participate in verbal exchanges in real time, whether at the meeting place in person or by a phone call, video conference, or other means.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE V</em><br>Executive Committee</h4>

                    <p>SECTION 1. The management of the affairs of the Student Branch shall be in the hands of the Executive Committee, consisting of the duly elected officers of the Student Branch and the committee chairs. The President shall be the Chair of the Executive Committee.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. The Executive Committee shall be the governing body of the Student Branch and shall transact all business it deems advisable to fulfill executive responsibilities, including those not otherwise delegated by this Constitution. Members of the Executive Committee serving in multiple roles are limited to one vote on each matter being considered by the committee.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 3. Committee chairs shall be selected by their committees by election time. Committee chairs must be students of Purdue University and be in good standing with the Purdue IEEE Student Organization. A committee chair may also serve as an elected officer and chair any number of other committees. Under most circumstances, committee chairs shall enjoy the same privileges as elected officers.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 4. The President is the ex officio Chair of the Branch in regards to reports to IEEE. Similarly, the Vice President is the ex officio Vice-Chair of the Branch.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 5. The Primary Advisor, secondary advisors, and Branch Counselor appointed by the IEEE shall act as honorary members of the Executive Committee. No term limits apply to the advisors or Branch Counselor.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 6. In the event of the graduation or resignation of an officer or committee chair, the departing officer or committee chair may nominate a successor to be voted in by the remaining officers and committee chairs. In the case of a failed vote, the President may nominate the next successor to take office subject to a vote by the same.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 7. An officer or committee chair may be recalled from office pending an announcement of a recall vote made at least one week in advance. A recall vote is successful if two-thirds of the Executive Committee present and voting except the member in question vote to remove that member. Alternatively, a general assembly of IEEE members that includes at least two members from each committee not serving on the Executive Committee may recall an elected officer with a two-thirds vote. Recalled officers or committee chairs may not nominate successors and may additionally be subject to the disciplinary actions given in Article III, Section 7 provided that the conditions given in said section are met.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE VI</em><br>Officers and Duties</h4>

                    <p>SECTION 1. The President shall preside at all meetings of the Student Branch. He or she shall promote and support the activities of the committees, cultivate communication between members, manage member activities, and bring attention to the advantages of IEEE membership. Furthermore, he or she shall strive to acquaint himself or herself with knowledge pertaining to the history of the organization.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. The Vice President shall perform the functions of the President in the latter’s absence or at his or her request. He or she shall assist the President in duties such as spreading awareness of IEEE, maintain good relations with other student organizations and the local community, and organizing IEEE and the committees.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 3. The Treasurer is tasked with overseeing the finances of IEEE and its committees. The Treasurer keeps accounts, deposits the organization’s funds, and makes expenditures in a manner approved by the Business Office for Student Organizations. He or she shall advance a budgetary plan for each academic year.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 4. The Secretary shall keep a record of all activities of the Student Branch as a whole. He or she shall report all organization activities to IEEE Headquarters, together with any special reports required by IEEE Headquarters, within a reasonable time after each meeting. The Secretary shall carry on all other communications necessary to the activities of the Branch. The secretary shall keep a record of the names of members in attendance at the meetings and shall forward efforts to recognize members for their technical accomplishments and service inside and outside the organization.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 5. The Industrial Relations Head shall organize events for corporate sponsors and serve as a point of contact for them. He or she shall focus on the acquisition and retention of sponsors in addition to the explanation and recommendation of them to students. Additional members may be appointed to assist in these duties at his or her leisure.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 6. The Event Coordinator bears the responsibility of organizing social functions and arranging professional development activities for the benefit and enjoyment of the members. The Event Coordinator shall lead efforts to promote membership in IEEE and encourage attendance at organization events through flyering, social media, etc. Additional members may be appointed to assist in these duties at his or her leisure.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 7. A complete annual Student Branch Activity report shall be prepared for submission by the President and Treasurer by May 1, and shall be submitted online to IEEE Member and Geographic Activities, upon review by the Secretary and certification by the Branch Counselor.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 8. Should the current President become unable to serve without nominating a successor, then the Vice President shall assume the office of President. Should both of those offices be vacant, then the succession proceeds down to the Treasurer, Secretary, Industrial Relations Head, and Event Coordinator in turn. The new President may then nominate a successor to the former office he or she held and any other vacant office subject to a vote by the Executive Committee.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE VII</em><br>Amendments</h4>

                    <p>SECTION 1. This Student Branch is empowered to adopt Bylaws that are consistent with this Constitution.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. The Executive Committee of IEEE may propose amendments to this Constitution during any of their meetings. Amendments pass only upon a vote of approval by two-thirds of the Executive Committee present and voting, provided that one more than half the number of Executive Committee members are present.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 3. All amendments to the Constitution and Bylaws are subject to the approval of the Office of the Dean of Students. Amendments may not take effect until after approval.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE VIII</em><br>Dues</h4>

                    <p>SECTION 1. The Executive Committee of the Branch shall have the power to levy special assessments for the present time up to two years in the future upon endorsement by a two-thirds vote of the officers and committee chairs present and voting. Upon expiration of the assessment period, a continuance or new assessment is required to continue collecting dues following a two-thirds vote of the same.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. Nonpayment of local dues by the date voted on by the members may result in suspension of membership in the local Student Branch, but will not result in suspension of membership at the international professional organization level.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE IX</em><br>Committees</h4>

                    <p>SECTION 1. Standing committees may be established by a majority vote of the elected officers to be founded under the goals and leadership of the committee chair that the elected officers choose. These standing committees may be disbanded upon mutual agreement of the President and the corresponding committee chair so long as the latter position is filled or upon a two-thirds vote of the Executive Committee, provided that one more than half the number of Executive Committee members are present.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. Committees shall select their own chair by election time each year. The committee chair shall establish a method of governance for the committee consistent with this Constitution. Each committee is responsible for outlining its own goals and purposes and drawing membership from the Student Branch as a whole.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 3. Each committee may determine its own requirements for committee membership and schedule for events and meetings. Each committee chair shall report the activities, meetings, and communications of its committee to the officers and other committee chairs. </p>

                    <p>SECTION 4. Each committee is expected to operate within its own budget as part of the operations of the IEEE. In accordance with the guidelines imposed by the Business Office of Student Organizations, the Treasurer must make deposits and authorize expenditures for all organization accounts.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 5. Committees may participate in competitions, exhibitions, and the like under their own name rather than that of the Purdue IEEE Student Organization if the organization as a whole is not actively participating in such events. The committee chair is responsible for securing permission from the President and Primary Advisor if needed.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 6. Joint projects between student organizations of a scope in time, labor, or cost that the Executive Committee deems significant shall be formalized in a project charter. Project charters should cover the allotment of participating members, finances, tools, workspace, and other resources. Concerns such as project ownership and duration should be addressed within. Project charters should be signed by the appropriate representatives of the Executive Committee following passage by a majority vote of the members present and voting and the corresponding governing bodies of other student organizations.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE X</em><br>Meetings</h4>

                    <p>The Student Branch shall hold regular and special meetings beyond the meetings of the committees at such places and time as designated by the Executive Committee, with a minimum of three meetings per academic year.</p>

                    <br><h4 class="text-center"><em>ARTICLE XI</em><br>IEEE Computer Society</h4>

                    <p>In acknowledgement of the former status of the Computer Society as an independent student organization, these special items shall apply in addition to those in Article IX:</p>

                    <p>SECTION 1. The Computer Society of the Purdue IEEE Student Organization shall not be disbanded and shall house the Student Branch Chapter of the IEEE Computer Society at the Purdue University-West Lafayette campus and operate in accordance with the Constitution and Bylaws of the IEEE Computer Society.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 2. The IEEE Computer Society shall select a Chapter Faculty Advisor from the faculty of Purdue University who is a member of both IEEE and the IEEE Computer Society. This individual may also act as the Primary Advisor or a secondary advisor of the student organization or the Branch Counselor.</p>


                    <p>SECTION 3. The members of IEEE Computer Society shall elect a Computer Society President prior to the elections of the Student Branch as a whole. The candidate eligibility, nominations, voting, and tie-breaking shall follow the requirements of Article IV of this Constitution. All voting of the IEEE Computer Society takes effect immediately.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 4. The Computer Society President is the ex officio Student Branch Chapter Chair of the IEEE Computer Society and Computer Society Chair of the committee within the Purdue IEEE Student Organization. He or she shall have jurisdiction over the affairs of the IEEE Computer Society and preside over its meetings. The Computer Society President may assume all other necessary executive duties or assign them to other executives that the Computer Society President appoints or brings to election.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 5. The IEEE Computer Society should follow the purposes laid out in Article II, with a focus on advancing the theory, practice, and application of computer and information processing science and technology and forming valuable relationships in this field.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 6. Upon appointment by the Computer Society President, the IEEE Computer Society may establish and disband subcommittees under the IEEE Computer Society under the goals and leadership of the subcommittee director that the Computer Society President chooses.</p>

                    <p>SECTION 7. Under most circumstances, the operations of the IEEE Computer Society are independent of the supervision of the Purdue IEEE Student Organization as a whole. Exceptions include the cases of financial transactions and administrative proceedings. Notification should be given for leadership changes and large activities.</p>
